Tuesday is the long-awaited first day and the doors will open at 8:00 am. Breakfast is served from 8:00-8:15 am daily. Students are tardy after 8:15 am.

We have missed our Bulldogs so much and are looking forward to a great year!!

2019-2020 Revenues Sources:
34% Local (taxes, lunch money, etc.)
9% County (railroad)
48% State (state formula based on student count)
9% Federal (Title I, Special Education)

In 2019-2020, only 27% of our Special Education expenses were covered by federal revenue. The remainder was paid from local funds.

In 2019-2020, only 27% of all transportation costs were covered by state revenues. The remainder was paid with local funds.

Source: Blackwater R-II Annual Secretary of the Board Report (ASBR)

post_text:
There is a misconception that the CARES relief money is to replace the revenues lost due to COVID-19. In fact, “the purpose of the CARES Act is to provide states with funding to prevent, prepare for and respond to the COVID-19 pandemic.” This includes cleaning and sanitizing products, PPE, technology and materials to prepare for long-term closures, etc. These funds are available on a reimbursable basis which means we have to spend the money before we receive it.

Source: Fiscal Guidance for Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security (CARES) Act Elementary and Secondary School Emergency Relief (ESSER) Fund - Sec. 1800

Official Ballot Language

Proposition 1:

Shall the Board of Education of the Blackwater R-II School District, Missouri, be authorized to increase the operating tax levy ceiling of the District by $1.50 per one hundred dollars of assessed valuation of real and personal property in order to provide additional funds to hire and retain qualified staff, better maintain its facilities, and to meet other operating needs of the District?

If this proposition is approved, the Board of Education agrees to increase the current operating levy by $0.75 in 2020 and the other $0.75 in 2022. The current operating levy of the district is $3.1080.

O YES
O NO

Blackwater PTO
July 18 at 2:36 PM ·

Officially a week away, Blackwater PTO is having a Dinner and Live Auction July 25th in place of our Annual Spring Carnival, which is our main and most important fundraising event, we had canceled due to covid-19. We are offering Drive-Thru services at the Kitchen door in the back of the school for those whom still would like to avoid crowds. We would love your support as this fundraiser will not only help by school supplies such as scissors, notebooks, hand sanitizer, pencils, and many of the other things that make leaning more productive in the classroom, it also helps fund incentives and field trips throughout the school year. Hopefully, this year will be as normal as possible. As always we are very thankful for any and all your support either by volunteering your time, buying a meal, donating auction items, or placing a bid on any of our fantastic auction items. THANK YOU

shared_text:
Boonville FFA Chapter
July 6 at 4:01 PM ·

Students didn’t get the chance to participate in their traditional Leadership Development Events this spring. Our District and State Association decided to formulate digital completions for students. Students were allowed to submit written materials electronically and then provide videos of their speeches, presentations, or interviews. Two individuals and one group decided to participate in the 2020 LDE competitions.

Caroline Herigon competed in Advanced Prepared Public Speaking and placed 2nd out of 15 contestants. Her manuscript and video will now be sent to state to compete.

The Agricultural Issues Forum Team of Maggie Davenport, Sydney Joy, Lilli Hendrix, Payton Luscombe, and Aidan Meyer placed 1st in Districts and their portfolio and video will know be sent for state judging.

Gracie Imhoff competed in Employment Skills and placed 8th out of 11 contestants.

We are so proud of these students and can’t wait to see how they do in at State competition!!

Boonslick Technical Education Center Boonville R-1 School District KWRT Radio

May 14 at 12:34 PM ·

MARCH AND APRIL PIRATE PRIDE:
Boonville High School is pleased to announce the March and April Pirate Pride award winners. The Pirate Pride Award is for students who have been outstanding at BHS. Teachers choose students based on a characteristic that has set him or her apart from the rest of the student body. These students may represent outstanding character, achievement, leadership, or service to the class or school. These award winners all share these characteristics.

Pirate Pride Award winners for March:
Gabe Brimer
Josiah Elwell
Aaron Witting
Sidney McKenzie
Brandon Mackey
Alexis Trigg
Nick Weixeldorfer
Peyton Keeran
Rose Gerry
Will Neckerman

Maddie Casey
Josie Widel
Layla Robinson
Adam Neckerman
Katera Bonaparte
Zeb Evans
Jordan Birk
Jalen Eby
Alison Unterreiner

Due to Covid-19 there was no ceremony or pictures taken.
As always, it is a GREAT day to be a Pirate!

Thank you,

Tim Edwards
BHS Principal

Write me a silly/funny story using the following story elements:

Characters: Mrs. Brown, your teacher (middle school-pick any teacher), and you

Setting: Wal-Mart

Problem: You grow eagle wings, Mrs. Brown grows rhino horns, and your teacher moos like a cow every 5 minutes.

Solution: You have to play hide and seek and not get found for one hour.

Send me your creative and silly stories! I can't wait to read them!

shared_text:
Jenni Henks Harvey is with Tanya Brown.
April 16 at 2:38 PM ·

“The Little Red Hen”. This is a three video lesson. Story and then two videos with 3 letter words. For this activity I would have magnet lowercase letters on the board with the boxes. The students would name the characters and I would place pictures to go with. We would take turns finding the letter for the sound and place it in the box. I miss getting to see their little brains work and the excitement when they could pick the letter. I would follow up with the little book for them to fill in and take home to read to mom and dad!!!

post_text: Blackwater R-II School District is seeking qualified candidates for a full-time teacher. The teacher is responsible for teaching Health, Technology, and PE. For the 2020-2021 school year, Blackwater R-II will run on a 4-day school week. Interested applicants must have a valid Missouri teaching certificate, preferably in PE, Health Education or Computer Technology. Base pay for position is $29,000 per year. Actual pay is based on previous experience. A certified staff application is available on the school's website at www.blackwater.k12.mo.us. Application, two letters of recommendation, and copy of current certificate can be emailed to tbrown@blackwater.k12.mo.us or mailed to PO Box 117, Blackwater MO 65322. Questions can be directed to Tanya Brown, Superintendent at 660-846-2461.

Cooper Co. Public Health Center
March 18 at 6:08 PM ·

The Cooper County Public Health Center is advising citizens to use reliable sites for Covid-19 information and news updates. Community gossip is running rampant. As of 5:55pm at the time of this release there are no known or presumptive cases of Covid-19 that has been reported to our office. Earlier today our office investigated misinformation and or gossip about a presumptive case. The information was false and a non-Cooper County citizen has been diagnosed with influenza. Please go to the websites: Missouri Department of Health and Senior Services, Centers for Disease Control (CDC), Johns Hopkins Covid-19 site or follow the Cooper County Public Health Center Facebook site or webpage under Public Notices for real information. Gossip and rumors do not benefit anyone. They increase panic and waste staff time investigating and tracking all parties involved. Thank you very much.
Respectfully,
Melanie Hutton RN, MSN
Administrator

post_text: The Board of Education will hold a special meeting tonight at 5:00 pm to discuss school closing due to the COVID-19 virus.
text: The Board of Education will hold a special meeting tonight at 5:00 pm to discuss school closing due to the COVID-19 virus.

post_text:
Parents:

Please know that we are continuing to assess our current situation with regards to school closure and COVID-19. Thanks to all parents who so quickly responded on the question of Internet access at home. We are keeping the survey results in mind as we move forward.

School will be in session tomorrow, Tuesday, March 17, 2020. We, like most other districts, are making these decisions on a day-to-day basis. I will post decisions on this page, as well as through Remind, when they are made.

These are unprecedented times that we are facing. Thank you for your understanding and patience and know that I am making the best decisions I can with the information given. If you prefer that your child stay home to minimize exposure, please communicate that with me. These absences will not count against attendance. Students will be expected to complete homework and may be picked up at the end of the school day.

As always, please don’t hesitate to contact me with questions.

Mrs. Brown

Boonslick Technical Education Center
December 19, 2019 at 3:21 PM ·

Join me in congratulating BTEC's newest National Technical Honor Society members!! Last night in front of proud families and friends, we inducted 19 new members into our local chapter of NTHS. These students have shown their drive and commitment to ensuring they have bright futures. We are so proud of their hard work and their continued focus on being the best community member, leader, and employee they can be. We heard about their work ethic, their civil responsibilities, and their dedication to making our world a better place. We are #BTECPROUD!! post_text: I am so proud of the 7th grade class. After reading the book, A Long Walk to Water, in Social Studies about the struggles that Sudan has with fresh water, the classmates decided they wanted to help. They organized a penny war they called “Water for Sudan” that involved the entire student body. They successfully raised $558.07 which will be sent to help the people of Sudan. Thank you to all the students who participated. The competition definitely got fierce! Congrats to the 5th grade class for earning the most “positive money” and winning the competition. A huge shout out to each of these 7th graders for their hard work to making this fundraiser a success. #pawpride

post_text:
Blackwater R-II is seeking qualified applicants to fill the following positions for the 2019-20 school year.

--Classroom teacher (full-time): Qualified applicants must possess a Missouri teaching certificate in Elementary Education.

--Art (2 days per week): Qualified applicants must possess or be able to obtain a Missouri teaching certificate in Art Education.

--Speech Therapist or Speech Implementer (2-3 days per week): Qualified Speech applicants must possess certificate from the Missouri Board of Healing Arts. Speech implementer must hold a valid Missouri teaching certificate.

--Music (2 days per week): Qualified applicants must possess or be able to obtain a Missouri teaching certificate in Music Education.

—Part-time Nurse: 1.5 days per week. RN or LPN certificate preferred. Pay based on experience.

An application can be found at www.blackwater.k12.mo.us under the Employment tab.

--Speech Therapist or Speech Implementer (2-3 days per week): Qualified Speech applicants must possess certificate from the Missouri Board of Healing Arts. Speech implementer must hold a valid Missouri teaching certificate.

--Music (2 days per week): Qualified applicants must possess or be able to obtain a Missouri teaching certificate in Music Education.

—Part-time Nurse: 1.5 days per week. RN or LPN certificate preferred. Pay based on experience.

An application can be found at www.blackwater.k12.mo.us under the Employment tab.

post_text: Each year, I have the opportunity to nominate one senior for a $2,000 scholarship through our school’s insurance company. This year, my nominee was Tyler Schuster. I was so excited when I received a call on Monday that Tyler had been chosen. There are six scholarships given across the state. More than 250 applications were received, including 150 students with a 4.0 GPA. What a great privilege for our former Bulldog to be chosen! Congratulations Tyler!

post_text: For some people, a Sportsmanship Award is not an important award and is thought to be given out of pity. Any student of mine, past or present, knows that good Sportsmanship is #1 in my book, whether we win or lose. This award is voted on by administrators and coaches of the conference. This award is not only for the players and Coach Craft, but for any fan that has come out and cheered on and supported our Bulldogs this year. Here’s to another great year to be a Bulldog! #pawpride

post_text: Read below for changes to the Box Top program that earns money for our school.
shared_text:
Box Tops Moms
April 4, 2019 at 9:04 PM ·

Big changes are coming to Box Tops. Over the next few months you’ll begin to see a new way to earn cash for your school. A NEW and improved, user-friendly Box Tops mobile app will be ready in June. The new app will feature state-of-the-art technology that allows you to scan your store receipt, find participating products and instantly add Box Tops to your school’s earnings online. Eventually, the physical clips are going away, and the Box Tops program will become digital-only (look for the NEW Box Tops icon over the summer).
